People tracking devices are increasingly needed by parents to keep an eye on their children.
The fear of having a child is making more and more people think of GPS surveillance.
The system originally designed to search for cars can also track people's movements, helping in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Annika Janatko.
The device is about the size of a cheese box, but soon it may be only as big as a watch.
