"We try to tell everyone that this is not a spy, but another way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the Czech market's leading suppliers of surveillance equipment.
"I admit that in some cases, such devices may be misused, for example, when they are put in a bag for someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case".
"Mostly, customers actually buy it for security reasons", Pilin added.
He believes that a child should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dan Bockova points out that if a child doesn't want to wear anything like that, they'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be in control".
"They used to have high expectations for parents, but they can be turned off like these tracking devices", says Bočková.
She also said it was questionable whether such a facility would actually help in the event of an attack.
"In the case of a premeditated kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always make sure that the child has no electronics with him that could reveal his location".
"Now it's a phone".
"As they begin to expand their tracking devices, they will look for them, too, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising".
"In such cases, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, it admits that similar devices can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and passengers, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
'The device may be set to dispatch the position periodically after a certain period of time.'
'If it is damaged, at least the last location of the person concerned shall be available.'
"The more expensive devices have built-in tilt meters, so even if a person slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately send a position-specific warning", says Czech.
He says that a similar service can be provided by navigation smartphones, which can also upload special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are either devices similar to wax box-sized hangers or smaller mobile phones.
They're always at risk of losing them.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, a device that looks like a regular digital watch is being tested.
"It would have the greatest advantage that the potential aggressor may not have to know the tracking device at all".
"Or he'll only know them after a while, and that could give the police extra time", he adds.
