Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Punitive activity is more worrying than unemployment.
And Brazil considers many regions more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the latest Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
In this year's survey, which was conducted in September and early October, two related issues dominate.
The first is that Latin America is in a fairly cheerful mood.
The second is to increase stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several Pacific Rim countries in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are Democrats, which is down from the regional average (see Chart 2).
Around 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same as last year, but a large increase from 2001 when it was 25%. (Figure 3)
Some 34% said they trusted the House and 45% trusted the government, again the same as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, democracy in Latin America was undermined by the economic crisis.
The support was likely created during the global financial crisis because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Moreover, a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009, and fell again this year to 32 percent.)
However, mood varies widely from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in the widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where recessions have been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since the surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31% say they or their close relatives were either victims of crime last year, but this is down from 38% last year and also the lowest number since 1995.
The stronger economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that allows their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela agree (and 80% there support private enterprise), although their left-wing president Hugo Chávez owns many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the field, as noted by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to last year unchanged) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential respondent country in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
