It's not like that.
"It shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life", explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, U.K.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it showed high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to replace one another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus".
"As a result, organisms find it very difficult to separate these elements".
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it doesn't work, and when it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes", Anbar explained.
Scientists are gathering bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposing them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which is the bacteria's ability to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better when phosphorus is present, but because they can also survive by replacing arsenic, there is an increased possibility that a form of life using arsenic could naturally occur elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
