"Everybody here loves Ta Moka".
"He was a good leader and cared for his people", said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as the "cutter" for his cruelty during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander in this remote Khmer Rouge homeland in northwestern Cambodia remains popular, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered their rule, long-standing loyalty is also broken in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims at the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to confront publicly those who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks that for the first time explain the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers to children.
And in July, the UN and the Cambodian court together will hand down the first sentence of a former Khmer Rouge member, the former leader of the notorious Tuol Sleng violent gang, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the Ghost, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advance, unrest has grown among the Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to re-engage in Cambodian society.
"There is envy and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"Life among the Khmer Rouge was wonderful for them, but the regime became a symbol of evil".
"It's dividing families".
During the Khmer Rouge's rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese attacked and overthrew Pol Pot's government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its troops fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they started an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, following a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to its first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to move to a government that culminated in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who survived, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have fallen into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the days of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government positions in exchange for their weapons, their positions remain weak, as unskilled farmers.
"These people have had only minimal benefit from surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the utopic agrarian ideology of the regime".
"They were being raised without any idea of doing business".
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"The mosquito fed everyone".
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of everything ourselves".
The ongoing Khmer Rouge trial has also raised concerns.
Early next year, the court will begin investigating Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute the executives and those responsible for the crimes, but it has not been said whether it will continue in the four cases.
It was enough to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was the regional leader in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that likely killed thousands of forced laborers.
On a recent steam evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to set and shadows appeared over the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable", she said.
"If there are any more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court sought further suspects, although experts and historians disagree.
"Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past in it", he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer affairs means blinding the broken pieces", he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so we can understand each other".
The Centre has published the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, which has 75 pages and is titled "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as an addition to the Ministry of Education's history booklet, which contains fewer than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng knew little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's connection to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School said the new textbook helps students understand important parts of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he took the book home for study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and courts", he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process more complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks, and the courts are starting to have an impact, he said.
The Khmer Rouge still have a strong magic here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a path of weeds and discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black sacs covered with carved sheet roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after he died in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone salesman, said she doesn't know much about the man who was cremated at the scene.
"But he has a strong spirit, and many locals come here and pray to him", she said.
Nuom Sothea was having her birthday and was planning to visit Pol Pot's resting place later, where she would bring a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing her luck.
