Belarus will be seventh.
Dozens of countries have done so under George W. Bush.
At the time of the Obama Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko announced that his nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the basis for the weapon and less enriched uranium", Lukashenko said afterwards.
"It's our commodity... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell it to anyone".
"We're only using it for research purposes, that's all".
However, Belarus joined the United States a few months ago and expressed an interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to remove Belarusian uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was lightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 1,300 miles to a Russian storage and disposal facility, officials said.
The second operation was completed Monday and was conducted by air, officials said.
The U.S. government has spent $13 million on the program, most of it on supplying the Belarusian research institute with less enriched uranium, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
"Everything was very carefully coordinated and managed on the basis of trust", leading to the Clinton-signed agreement, said Andrew Bieniawski, a Department of Energy official working for Global Threat Reduction.
The James Martin Center for Nuclear Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of uranium used for weapons production.
According to the Joint Declaration, Belarus will endeavour to remove its stocks by 2012.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, primarily because of Lukashenko's brutal crackdown on human rights.
