And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is going to be, which refers to the idea of keeping to old traditions that a large part of the rest of the membership holds.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, for example, while the southern countries would leave the currency zone.
The second is the return to the march -- although it may now seem like science fiction, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to restructure the euro with greater macroeconomic oversight, budgetary constraints, fines for the guilty states, possible deferrals in payments for some of them, and with the extension of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
