This was the first sign of a conflict between what Germany considered to be correct (fiscal rigidity and public finance stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel painfully challenged the Greek rescue decision.
Already at the time, it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion that was also published were strongly against saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again came out with a clear stance when she called for reforming the European Union's conventions to allow a rescue of a Member State while also making private creditors liable to bear some of the costs.
This opinion has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although somewhat mitigated, was approved and we should follow the Union's reform process over the coming months, which should allow for such measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it will not cross.
