Sport and circumvention
The finties Alonso and Ramos showed against Ajax show wit, not intent on evasion.
The allegedly planned exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramose) from the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be written on whether or not this was unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether UEFA should not punish both players.
As is well known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the nominees deliberately wasted time one after the other at the time the foul was to be played to provoke the referee, who showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet their penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing top of their group - and will be able to proceed to the next stage, having been stripped of their card.
In the end, UEFA's disciplinary committee fined coach José Mourinh for two games and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos of football, which is rules that are unwritten, but followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that the participant was the Real Madrid team (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which already punished its players for similar acts), and also apparently due to the dramatization led by Mourin, who thus adds to his long history of comedian and provocateur another episode.
In any event, the debate is whether this kind of action, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is circumvention of the law in the act; it is indeed an action respecting the rules of sport, the meaning of which, however, seems to be circumvented.
The damage caused by such conduct to the spirit of sport is determined.
One of the characteristics of sporting conduct is the physical integrity of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. no violent play occurred.
Another feature of pure play is to avoid giving players an advantage over an opponent's team because of their offense - which has not happened here either.
So the paradox of the Real Madrid players' actions is that what we normally call a deception or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules to avoid sanctions, but rather that this behavior was to be as obvious as possible to get punishment.
They waited and were happy to get the punishment.
The next question is, however, what benefit will those guilty of their deliberate transgression gain?
It must be noted here that the opponent is not placed at a disadvantage and that he will not gain any advantage in the current match, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage is obviously that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is a long-term advantage with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and yet by doing so, the players will reverse their punishment and move on to the second round of cards, where one card is enough to eliminate the first round.
So as the wheels continue, it's not entirely clear if this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations are not against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that allow for maximum benefit under the rules.
In the case we're dealing with, players were not meant to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather to choose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between wit and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that it was clearly wit in this case.
I think the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way the instructions were passed on to the management to provoke them.
The violation of sporting principles by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
