The United States Amends the Rules for Visa
People will have to go to the Visa Applicant Services Centre before the interview at the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa negotiation process at the U.S. Embassies and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Service Centre (ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will collect the applicant's biometric information and will be evaluated by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of issuing a visa will be lower, with no more fees for arranging a meeting, one for processing an application and another for delivering a document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for a business and investor visa.
People wishing to renew their visas will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
As biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview with the Consular Section will spend less time here than in the past.
Also, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer be charged an extra fee of $26 for the service.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
