The World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The UN yesterday proposed a plan in Cancun to restore domestic lighting, lighting of commercial and industrial premises in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse effect (GHE) limitation, which is almost one third of the additional limitation to be achieved to stabilize the planet's climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Cancun to compensate for the lack of difficult-to-realize reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the bulbs that are lit, which still hold 50 to 70% of the market, were to be replaced by fluorocompact or, even better, LED bulbs, the substantial amount of 1.8 billion tonnes of GES emissions from lighting on the planet would be cut off.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from fleet cars on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will take another 5 Gt off this balance to achieve a 2°C stabilisation of climate warming by 2020 so that it can be ruled out getting out of control.
In light bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5% is the product of light.
With fluorocompact bulbs, we're cutting energy consumption by 75%, and with new LED bulbs, we're cutting energy consumption by another two times.
Fluocompact bulbs will last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, the ones Philips introduced this week - which reportedly participated in a UN study - have an expected lifetime of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a light bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
All of these new bulbs can also work with reostates and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries,unless producers set up collectors.
However, the report notes that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluorocompact light bulbs but rather thermal coal-fired power plants, which emit much of the mercury needed to generate the electricity wasted in the light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants produce 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report also details the gains each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 billion heating plants.
