Snow and ice: 24 counties have an orange emergency.
Snowfall is still causing traffic problems, especially on second-class roads in Brittany, and there is a risk that it will disrupt some economic activities.
Twenty-four counties are now in an orange emergency due to the risk of snow and ice.
L'Eure, l'Eure-et-Loir, les Deux-Sèvres and la Vienne have joined the 20 districts already declared to be in an orange emergency, 18 as of Wednesday afternoon and two, la Dordogne and la Gironde, later in the night.
According to Météo France, heavy snowstorms are causing problems in the north of La Gironde and Les Charentes and slight snowfall in Ile-de-France.
A snow cover of 2 to 5 cm, places of 7 to 10 cm, is expected in the districts concerned and a cover of 1 to 3 cm, places of 5 in the Paris region.
The districts of Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d'Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, du Poitou and the districts of the regions of Basse-Normandie, Ile-de-France and Limousin are affected.
Snowstorms are large enough to cause traffic problems and disrupt some economic activities, predicts Météo France.
On the Côtes d'Armor coast, some districts have banned heavy goods traffic - trucks over 7.5 tonnes on the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac routes.
Traffic on second-class roads in Brittany is very difficult, police say, and police recommend that you only drive when it is really necessary and some trucks have been cancelled for the day.
School holidays were banned in Picardy on Thursday.
No special measures are envisaged to restrict freight transport on Wednesday evening.
The district authority "calls on all motorists to exercise the utmost caution on the roads and to adapt the driving character of the road".
