The hacks and the scouts
The WikiLeaks case has two meanings.
On the one hand, there is a clear scandal, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future of regress controlled.
But let's get it right.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the fact that every document compiled by a secret service (any nation) is made up entirely of press clippings.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's sexual lifestyle tell them what anyone could read in any newspaper for months (all but these two Berlusconi owned), and Gaddafi's infamous caricature profile has long been a subject of sketches for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret documents should consist only of messages already known is fundamental to the dynamics of the secret service, and not just this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you'll find that every work (about the Grail, the Rennes-le-Château mystery, the Templars or the Woodmen) repeats exactly what was already written in previous works.
Not only does the author of occult texts hate to look for new information (or not know where to look for information about nonexistent ones), but those who practice the occult only believe what they already know and confirm what they have learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same goes for classified documents.
The informant is a lazy, lazy (or limited in spirit) head of the secret service (and if he isn't, he could be, as far as I know, the editor of the Libération newspaper), who only believes what he confesses to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the state department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published a week earlier.
So why was there so much talk about these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person knows, that since the end of World War II, at least, and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly out to dinner together, embassies have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representative exercises, have been transformed into a spy centre.
Any viewer of investigative films knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it is seemingly ignored.
However, the fact that it is repeated publicly dishonors the duty of hypocrisy and throws a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could gain access to the most highly classified information of the world's most powerful country is a hard blow, not a negligible blow, to the prestige of this state resort.
The scandal affects both the victims and their "executives".
But let's get to the truth about what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, it was possible to conceive of all power as some Big Brother controlling every movement of his people.
Orwell's prophecy has been proven since the ability to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, every hotel visited, every highway used, and so on, made a citizen a complete victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate how things are now, that even "grave tombs" with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circuit.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker -- elected as a citizen's avenger -- can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be maintained that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that a true secret is a bottomless secret (and bottomless secrets can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a topless secret because it is taken out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secret was bottomless secrets is to deprive him of all power.
WikiLeaks didn't make any mistakes with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will the consequences of this wound of power be so significant?
Clearly, in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - the same as posting it on a street corner poster.
But it's also quite obvious that with current technology, there's no reason to hope that you can keep a phone message secret.
There's nothing easier than knowing if and when the head of state flew in and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future ?
I know my predictions are science fiction at this point, and so they're fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who are discreetly carrying out formalities on uncontrollable routes and carrying only the messages they know by heart or rather hide the rare information in their shoes.
The information will be stored in unique copies in key-locked drawers: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has rehabilitated the telegraph based on wires.
Video cassettes (analog) allowed movie lovers to shoot the film step by step, moving it back and forth and revealing all the secrets of the setup, while now CDs (number) only allow you to skip through the chapters, i.e. through the macroporters.
We can get from Rome to Milan by express train in three hours, while the plane and transportation that it takes takes us three and a half hours.
It is no wonder that politics and communication technology are returning to horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
On other occasions, the press tried to understand what was going on in the embassy's secret.
Now it's the embassies asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its pledges of funding
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the promise of rapid unblocked financing (or early-start financing) implemented by developed countries.
And the great French hooks were revealed
In the Copenhagen Accord, the developed countries committed to providing $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million a year).
At the start of COP16, the EU has taken a big step to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report clarifying its Member States' actions, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its pledge of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we look at the details, we find things are much more complicated.
The Commission therefore considers that the aid is compatible with the internal market and that the aid is compatible with the internal market.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding was preserved and it is adding 150 million to it for three years under the title of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or deadlines at the level of public development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words,there is no reference to the expenditure of the previous periods or to the global level of public aid for development.
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even reduced), in order to comply with its commitment to finance 'new and additional ...'.
Another crucial factor is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There's no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, consider that a loan is equal to a donation.
Obviously, it's hard to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects linked to emission reductions based on more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro we receive as the equivalent of one euro we give... we should not understand it from the title of our commitments but as the price of the loan for the creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only give this justification: it 'complies' with its €420 million commitment, making 91.5% of it loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document for your own sake.
It is the only Union country to use the loan on such a scale.
Germany requested 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) comply with their 100% contribution commitments.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 per month to fulfil its promise, it will give France only 10 cents and consider this an equivalent effort.
That's a beautiful piece of cabbage!
In summary, in its 'fast start' financing, France operates with a double-edged approach: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time and on the other hand, with a real financial burden.
Although he spends only 36.1 million euros, he can convince himself that he is spending 420 million euros "new and additional" in keeping with his promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that Bercy made the decision) could have a double negative impact both within the EU (why would member states continue to give when all they need to do is borrow?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early financing is only a small question, relatively short term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in a giant machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
France should first notify a change in its accounting practices for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and justice towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid the discussion of long-term financing investments (another essential chapter currently being discussed): we cannot avoid the question of 'sufficiency' or how loans are accounted for.
France should change its position to become as progressive in these deposits as it is in others.
So everyone's hoping for the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Moritz, who will be arriving in Cancun next week.
