Alert about pesticides that children are watching.
A 10-year-old child will one day look at 81 different chemicals, according to a study published Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (formerly the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which notes that its results "have no significant statistical value given the low number of samples analysed but are characteristic of the processed issue", purchased between July and September food commonly consumed in four meals and one light snack per child for about a decade in supermarkets in L'Oise and Paris.
These typical foods, including the official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - and sugar products, were analysed by the research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are among the clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as a disruptor to the internal carotid gland (IP), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we clearly see that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogens, and/or PE is staggering", the association states.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain about 10 residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported in a study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same is true for the Kenyan green beans included for lunch, where the study found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, ground meat steaks, canned tuna, and even peas and chewing gum were contaminated with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform in the tap water.
The salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave did not escape analysis.
The final risk to consumers of this 'contaminant cocktail' is likely to be underestimated,' the study shows.
The Ecological Europe-Green (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on pesticide use to halt the "growth of civilization diseases" "in the face of an emergency".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the residue status of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which were in cereals.
